{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"26c46d21-ae07-47c1-b808-85bc7a543f31","content":"These are two distinct issues introduced by C# 15 / .NET 11 changes:\n\n---\n\n**1. `DynamicOps.cs` — `&&` with `dynamic` and interface operators**\n\nThe `&&` operator desugars to `T.false(left) ? left : T.&(left, right)`. When `right` is `dynamic`, the entire expression was historically deferred to the DLR runtime binder. However, the **DLR binder does not support resolving `operator true`/`operator false` defined on interface types** — it only looks at class types.\n\nIn C# 15, the compiler now catches this at compile time (previously it would compile but fail at runtime). Since `left` is typed as `IFilter` (an interface), the compiler can't guarantee the DLR will find the required `operator false`/`operator true`.\n\n**Fix options:**\n- Use a concrete type instead of the interface: `void Apply(CompositeFilter left, dynamic right)`\n- Decompose the `&&` manually:\n  ```csharp\n  var combined = IFilter.false(left) ? left : (IFilter)((dynamic)left & right);\n  ```\n\n---\n\n**2. `RefHelper.cs` — CS0518 with `ref readonly` lambda return**\n\nCS0518 (\"Predefined type is not defined or imported\") means the compiler needs a well-known BCL type that isn't present in your target framework. In C# 15, `ref readonly` return types on **lambda expressions** require a new attribute (likely `System.Runtime.CompilerServices.RequiresLocationAttribute` or a similar metadata type) to encode the `ref readonly` semantics on the synthesized delegate.\n\nThis happens when there's a **mismatch between the compiler and target framework** — typically the SDK was upgraded but the project still targets an older TFM.\n\n**Fix:** Ensure your project targets `net11.0`:\n```xml\n<TargetFramework>net11.0</TargetFramework>\n```\n\nIf you're multi-targeting or can't move to .NET 11 yet, you can work around it by using an explicit delegate type instead of a lambda:\n\n```csharp\ndelegate ref readonly int RefReadonlyFunc();\n\npublic static void M()\n{\n    RefReadonlyFunc fn = ref readonly int () => ref value;\n}\n```\n\nOr define the missing type as a polyfill if needed.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"b28e6694-60c7-490e-8405-ffc4897b861e","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about two new compiler errors they're encountering after upgrading to .NET 11 / C# 15. Let me analyze both cases.\n\n**Case 1: `DynamicOps.cs` - `left && right` with dynamic**\n\nThis is about the `&&` operator with a `dynamic` right operand and an interface type left operand that defines `operator true`/`operator false`.\n\nIn C# 15 / .NET 11, there were changes related to how the compiler handles short-circuit operators (`&&`, `||`) with `dynamic` operands. The `&&` operator is syntactic sugar for a combination of `operator true`/`operator false` and `operator &`. When one operand is `dynamic`, the binding is deferred to runtime. \n\n\nThe issue is that `IFilter` defines static operators `true` and `false` directly on the interface, and in C# 15 the compiler's handling of how these interact with `dynamic` operands has shifted. I need to think through whether this is about the compiler no longer being able to resolve the operator at compile time when `dynamic` is involved, or if there's a specific restriction about using interface-defined operators in this context. C# 11 introduced static abstract members in interfaces, so that's not the issue. The real problem is likely a breaking change in how the compiler handles `dynamic` with user-defined conditional logical operators—when `right` is `dynamic`, the entire expression becomes dynamic, but the compiler still needs to verify at compile time that the type has both `operator &` and `operator true`/`operator false`. In C# 15 or .NET 9+, there may have been changes to how overload resolution works with `dynamic` in these contexts.\n\nDefining the operators... the compiler now requires compile-time resolution of `operator true`/`operator false` even when dealing with `dynamic` operands, which would be a significant shift from earlier versions where such operations were deferred to runtime. I'm trying to pinpoint whether the breaking change relates to how interfaces handle user-defined operators or how the compiler treats `&&` with mixed static and dynamic types.\n\nFor the second error with `ref readonly` lambdas, the issue seems to be that C# 15 introduced support for `ref readonly` return types in lambda expressions, but this requires a runtime type or attribute that isn't available—possibly something like `RequiresLocationAttribute`—and when that's missing, the compiler throws CS0518 about a predefined type not being defined. to be more strict about type checking in dynamic expressions, or there's a new requirement for explicit operator resolution that wasn't needed before. This could explain why the code that worked in earlier versions now fails with CS0518. likely the compiler now requires resolving `operator false` at compile time even with `dynamic` operands, and since `IFilter` is an interface, the runtime binder can't handle interface-level operators—so I'd need to cast to a concrete type, manually separate the short-circuit logic, or use a concrete type instead. There's also a possibility this relates to a new C# 15 feature around `ref readonly` return types on lambdas.\n\nFor the second case, `ref readonly` returns from lambdas might require a runtime type that isn't available—CS0518 suggests the compiler is looking for a predefined type that doesn't exist in the current target framework, so I'd need to ensure the project targets a newer .NET runtime that supports this feature. the compiler would need to synthesize an anonymous delegate type that returns `ref readonly int`, which requires encoding this in metadata using attributes like `In` or `RequiresLocationAttribute`. If the target framework doesn't have these types available, that's what triggers the CS0518 error. The fix would likely involve targeting `net11.0` or providing a polyfill for the missing attribute type.\n\nFor the `&&` operator case with `IFilter` and `dynamic`, the issue is that when evaluating `x && y`, the compiler needs to verify `operator false` exists on the left operand's type at compile time, then use `operator &` to combine them. In C# 15, it seems the compiler is being stricter about allowing these user-defined operators on interfaces, whereas previously it might have been more lenient with static abstract members.\n\nFor the `ref readonly` lambda returning CS0518, the compiler is likely missing a required BCL type or attribute needed to properly encode the `ref readonly` semantics in the synthesized delegate type's metadata. This typically indicates a mismatch between the compiler version and the target framework version. The compiler's handling of `operator false` on interface types with `dynamic` operands likely changed in C# 15, causing it to fail where it previously deferred to the DLR. The workaround is to avoid mixing interface-typed values with `dynamic` in short-circuit operators, or manually decompose the expression. For the second case, `ref readonly` returns on lambdas probably weren't supported before C# 15, or the metadata encoding now requires a well-known type that's missing, which is why the compiler can't find the predefined type it needs. I'm thinking through the specifics of these compiler errors. For the dynamic case, the issue is likely that C# 15 now properly detects when the runtime dynamic binder can't handle user-defined conditional operators on interface types—something that would have failed at runtime before but now gets caught at compile time. For the `ref readonly` lambda case, the synthesized delegate type needs a predefined attribute that only exists in newer .NET versions, so targeting .NET 11 or providing a polyfill would resolve it. I should give a straightforward explanation of both issues without overcomplicating it. I don't have concrete details about C# 15 yet, but I can work through what these error patterns suggest. The issue with `left && right` where `left` is an `IFilter` and `right` is `dynamic` comes down to how the conditional logical operators desugar—they rely on `operator false` and `operator &`, which the runtime binder historically couldn't handle properly on interface types. Earlier versions might have compiled but failed at runtime, whereas the compiler in this version is catching it upfront.\n\nFor the CS0518 error with `ref readonly int () => ref value`, that's pointing to a missing predefined type—almost certainly a new well-known type or attribute that came with .NET 11 to support `ref readonly` returns in lambdas. If the project isn't targeting .NET 11 or the SDK is out of date, the compiler can't find what it needs.","outputTokens":5248,"requestId":"D400:1CDDAB:24148F4:27378A4:69FBB907"},"id":"bc4e551a-87e0-4ebc-85cb-304c7ff2015d","timestamp":"2026-05-06T21:58:10.045Z","parentId":"3cba56a5-39d8-4f8d-8189-317d279e522f"}
